{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533450"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:35:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:35:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14784"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14784"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.45,0.02,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7475"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58611"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7475"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44013"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"358"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"3687"},{"type":"tags","id":"4249"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58611"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe left thigh pain that began 24 hours ago. The pain is disproportionate to examination findings and is rapidly worsening. He sustained a deep laceration to his thigh while operating machinery on a farm two days ago but did not seek medical attention at the time. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and distressed. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. His left thigh is diffusely tender with patchy erythema and induration. The skin appears tense and shiny with areas of dusky discolouration. Blood tests reveal a white cell count of 22 x 10^9/L (4-11) and C-reactive protein 280 mg/L (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus pyogenes","Staphylococcus aureus","Escherichia coli","Bacteroides fragilis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of necrotising fasciitis, characterised by severe pain disproportionate to examination findings, rapid progression, and systemic toxicity following traumatic injury. The presence of tense, shiny skin with dusky discolouration is consistent with streptococcal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvasive Group A Streptococcal disease is defined as infection where \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E is isolated from a normally sterile site (such as blood, cerebrospinal fluid, or deep tissue). \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/strong\u003E (Group A Streptococcus) is a common cause of necrotising fasciitis, particularly when presenting with severe pain disproportionate to examination findings. The infection typically spreads rapidly along fascial planes, causing tissue destruction and systemic toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of soft tissue infections but rarely causes such rapidly progressive, severe infection. It typically causes cellulitis or abscesses, or can be involved in polymicrobial necrotising fasciitis, but would not explain this presentation alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E can occasionally cause severe soft tissue infections, particularly in diabetic patients or immunocompromised hosts, but is not typically associated with this type of rapidly progressive infection following trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacteroides fragilis\u003C/strong\u003E is an anaerobic organism that can be involved in polymicrobial soft tissue infections but is rarely the sole pathogen. It is not typically associated with the rapid progression and severity seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E can cause severe soft tissue infections, particularly in immunocompromised patients or following water exposure, but this pattern of rapidly progressive infection is more consistent with Invasive Group A Streptococcal disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case requires immediate surgical debridement along with high-dose intravenous antibiotics. The combination of penicillin and clindamycin is typically used to treat streptococcal necrotising fasciitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Group A streptococcal necrotising fasciitis typically presents with severe pain disproportionate to examination findings","Early signs of necrotising fasciitis can be subtle, with rapid progression to systemic toxicity","Necrotising fasciitis requires immediate surgical debridement and high-dose antibiotics"],"references":["McDermott J, Kao LS, Keeley JA, Grigorian A, Neville A, de Virgilio C. Necrotizing Soft Tissue Infections: A Review. JAMA Surg. Published online September 11, 2024. doi:10.1001/jamasurg.2024.3365","Hua C, Urbina T, Bosc R, et al. Necrotising soft-tissue infections. Lancet Infect Dis. 2023;23(3):e81-e94. doi:10.1016/S1473-3099(22)00583-7"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44013"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14784"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44013"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-01T20:18:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-01T20:19:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7475"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58611"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,